SIMPLE: overblow
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Overblow
<hw>O`ver*blow"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
blow over, or be subdued.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To force so much wind into a pipe
that it produces an overtone, or a note higher than the natural note;
thus, the upper octaves of a flute are produced by
<xex>overblowing</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overblow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Overblow
<hw>O`ver*blow"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To blow away; to
dissipate by wind, or as by wind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When this cloud of sorrow's <qex>overblown</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To ascribe an unwarranted importance to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Music)</fld> <def>To blow into (a wind instrument)
too strongly, so as to produce predominantly overtones.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>overblown</ent>⟦br⟧
